{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4855fcbf-b9b5-44d7-b7e8-64e90a1b79b5","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can give you the key configuration needed. To publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool**, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThen **pack and publish**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUsers install and run it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `PackAsTool` makes it a global/local dotnet tool.\n- `ToolCommandName` sets the CLI command name.\n- `OutputType` must be `Exe` (required for tools).\n- Get your API key from [nuget.org/account/apikeys](https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys).\n\nWant me to scaffold the project with this configuration?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de15e861-b29b-4582-a216-a3d381d9fa49","outputTokens":421,"requestId":"B023:166A0:D692BC:F37896:6A027DC9"},"id":"494a05e0-cc7d-4e34-9ef2-b07d90178461","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:09:37.413Z","parentId":"d4097503-68d8-4417-b605-7b399f1f7893"}
